✅ In one line:

An inline function in C++ is a small function whose code is expanded at the call site to reduce function call overhead — but 
the compiler decides whether to actually inline it.

--> It’s like copy-pasting the function’s body wherever it’s used.


🔹 Syntax

    You can declare a function as inline in two ways:
        ✅ 1. Inside the class definition (automatically inline means implicitly inline), If the fuction has defination
            Note: If only declartion, definaton later, it is not considered as inline (Explicily you can make inline)
        
        ✅ 2. Using the inline keyword

🔹 Purpose

    The main goals of inline functions are:

        🚀 Reduce function call overhead

            Avoids pushing arguments to the stack and jumping to a new address.

        ⚡ Faster execution for very short functions

            Especially for getters/setters or small arithmetic utilities.

🔹 When (and When Not) to Use
✅ Use Inline	                                                     
1. Very short, frequently called functions	                         
2. Simple mathematical or accessor functions	                     
3. Functions defined in headers (templates, class methods)	

❌ Avoid Inline
   Large or complex functions
   Functions with loops, recursion, or static variables
   When code size increase outweighs call overhead
